RGB to Irradiance¶

I rendered a tilted plane in C4d using sky, ground and sun objects. This is my first attempt at mapping the rendered images of the plane to solar irradiance

Compare Grayscale with Irradiance¶

Compute grayscale timeseries from all frames and compare with clearsky irradiance model for the same time period and location.

Note that this is irradiance on a horizontal plane while the 3d model was tilted! This should be fixed by either "untilting" the model or by deriving irradiance in the tilted plane. I'll fix this later. Also I dont yet know how important the proportions of the 3d model are, but I assume getting them "realistic" will be necessary in the future.

In [6]:
def filename2mean(fn):
    """ read image and compute grayscale mean value """
    img = imageio.imread(fn)
    gray = cv2.cvtColor(img, cv2.COLOR_BGR2GRAY)
    return gray.mean()

vals = np.array([filename2mean(fn) for fn in filenames])
In [7]:
dr = pd.date_range("2019-08-26T10:00:00", "2019-08-26T11:15:36", periods=len(vals))

dr -= pd.Timedelta("2h") # I think c4D is in localtime, but pvlib needs UTC. Not sure though!

Mapping¶

Mapping of grayscale values to ghi values using a linear model.

In [10]:
reg = linear_model.LinearRegression()

train_x, train_y = vals[:150], irr.ghi.iloc[:150].values
test_x, test_y = vals[150:], irr.ghi.iloc[150:].values


reg.fit(train_x.reshape(-1, 1), train_y.reshape(-1, 1))
reg.coef_, reg.intercept_
Out[10]:
(array([[3.27868908]]), array([230.69187951]))
In [11]:
result_train = reg.predict(train_x.reshape(-1, 1))[:, 0]

df = pd.DataFrame()
df["clearsky model"] = train_y
df["image"] = result_train

df.plot()
plt.title("Training Set")
plt.ylabel("Irradiance [W/m²]")
Out[11]:
Text(0, 0.5, 'Irradiance [W/m²]')
